  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence, captive rearing of bumblebees for reintroduction has shown mixed outcomes with several significant challenges. Twenty-two trials from 13 countries have documented captive rearing of bumblebee colonies using various methods including confining mated queens alone, with bumblebee workers, honey bee workers, male bumblebee pupae, or following CO2 anaesthetisation (Action 50). \n\nFor North American declining species, outcomes varied significantly. Two trials successfully induced spring queens of half-black bumblebee B. vagans to rear adults in captivity, and one trial succeeded with queen yellow-banded bumblebees B. terricola and red-belted bumblebees B. rufocinctus. However, all three trials attempting to rear yellow bumblebee B. fervidus failed as queens laid eggs but larvae died before becoming adults, with the same mortality pattern observed for rusty-patched bumblebee and American bumblebee B. pensylvanicus (Action 50).\n\nKey factors affecting success include diet quality, with buff-tailed bumblebee B. terrestris colonies fed freshly frozen pollen producing larger queens with better survival and larger colonies compared to those fed dried, frozen pollen. Higher protein content pollen also increased offspring production (Action 50). Hibernation protocols showed that queens hibernated at 4-5\u00b0C for 45 days had enhanced egg-laying and colony formation rates, though they produced smaller colonies than non-hibernated queens. Queens weighing more than 0.6 g and hibernated for four months or less had better survival chances (Action 50).\n\nFor reintroduction outcomes, seven replicated trials monitored laboratory-reared colony success in the environment. Results were variable - two UK trials produced very low or zero numbers of new queens, while two other trials produced good numbers of new queens (Action 52). A major challenge identified was social parasitism by cuckoo bees Bombus [Psithyrus] species, with high